AB  - This paper presents evidence on the costs and benefits for the U.S. banking system of a partial version of market value accounting in which only securities are marked to market. Because accounting for liabilities is unchanged, this accounting system has the same potential for misvaluing bank capital as historical cost accounting. Evidence from bank failure prediction models indicates the new system will not reduce bank failure rates. Other evidence indicates that net benefits will be small in absolute value, and of uncertain sign.
